Stage two

Attempt to partition the data

To be able to properly operate on the data, we needed to take the following steps to shape-up the data:

  • Group the records by schools
  • For each school store the average time for each task
  • Remove all tasks with more than 3000 NaNs
  • Replace NaNs with column means
  • Choose a smaller subset to ease the computations - 3000 schools

This is the final format of the data.

head(tabelka[0:5])

To group the schools (and further, diagnose the test-taking schemes), we have used the K-means method. Below, there are two 2-dimensional representations of the groups. The first one uses a projection of our design: the two axes are mean time of solving math tasks and mean time of solving reading tasks. The other one is a projection with classical scaling.

K-means - math / reading representation

K-means with classical scaling

Why three groups?

Itâ€™s necessary to explain why there are three groups chosen. One can see it on the following histogram, which shows the $ W(C) $ measure, which sum the distances between nodes in each group, for the K-means partitioning for 2 through 7 groups.

The choice seems justified now, as the leap between 3 and 4 groups doesnâ€™t seem to be tall enough to be considered.

Names for the groups

  • Group 1: the average
  • Group 2: the patient
  • Group 3: the fast and furious
